  • habitat is very heterogeneous and they are mixed (one species can be marine and freshwater??). We group in two variables: (habitat2)can consider all with freshwater as aquatic. The species with a mixed of marine and other are from saline environment habitat3 separating aquatic from terrestrial

  • Lifeform has many groups with extremely variable number of cases per level.

  • There are 723 records with lag data. fully exotic 501

  • There is a long tail towards negative lags ( citizen science very early). Now they correspond to Belgium and Sweden. - Be aware of very early citizen science dates. Up to 1990

Dataset - Check NumRecCS_Species (nOccTotSp) for NA values. There are 155 records without this variable. Not using it at the moment - There are some species with NA in top lists. Double check species_variable.csv

  • separating in two models depending on the tail
  • belgium overrepresented. Check with Tim.

  • Citizens are earlier when it has been observed in the country before (more negative), It is the most important
  • Faster for vertebrates than plants
  • Faster when there are more citizen records of the species
  • No effect of google or scopus hits
  • being in a priority list is marginally significant. worth completing gaps

#################Probar overdispersion - https://bbolker.github.io/mixedmodels-misc/glmmFAQ.html#fitting-models-with-overdispersion

overdisp_fun <- function(model) {
    rdf <- df.residual(model)
    rp <- residuals(model,type="pearson")
    Pearson.chisq <- sum(rp^2)
    prat <- Pearson.chisq/rdf
    pval <- pchisq(Pearson.chisq, df=rdf, lower.tail=FALSE)
    c(chisq=Pearson.chisq,ratio=prat,rdf=rdf,p=pval)
}

overdisp_fun(modelpos) # high and significant
##        chisq        ratio          rdf            p 
## 1.600054e+03 2.777872e+00 5.760000e+02 3.454676e-97
## extract summary table; you may also be able to do this via
##  broom::tidy or broom.mixed::tidy
quasi_table <- function(model,ctab=coef(summary(model)),
                           phi=overdisp_fun(model)["ratio"]) {
    qctab <- within(as.data.frame(ctab),
    {   `Std. Error` <- `Std. Error`*sqrt(phi)
        `z value` <- Estimate/`Std. Error`
        `Pr(>|z|)` <- 2*pnorm(abs(`z value`), lower.tail=FALSE)
    })
    return(qctab)
}
